<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission to the Transport Select Committee  inquiry about cycle safety.docx</title></head><body style="background:#ffffff"><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the Association o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">f Bikeability Schemes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (CYS0120)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">THE ASSOCIATION OF BIKEABILITY SCHEMES</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About TABS</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TABS is a trade association which works with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Department for Transport to ensure the highest quality of delivery of Bikeability cycle training. TABS aims to work in the interest of Bikeability schemes, and represents the view of the professional cycle training industry in discussions and decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-making activities with Government agencies and other public bodies. TABS’s ultimate aim is more people taking trips by bike more often and more safely.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chris Boardman submitted a statement expressing the support of the work that TABS is doing: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“Cycling </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">has never been more important than now in terms of promoting enjoyable physical activity.  Being able to ride a bike confidently on road, with minimum risk, is an essential life skill for an active and healthy lifestyle. Bikeability has an important role t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">o play in giving people of all ages, especially the next generation of young people and their parents, the skills and confidence to make everyday trips by bike. If we want to transform cycling in this country we need to do all we can to make a difference a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">nd make sure that the government is taking us seriously.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">I welcome the role of TABS in making the case for the continued funding for Bikeability beyond the term of this current government.”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TABS has been delivering courses across the sector aiming to ensu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re the consistency of the quality delivery of cycle training on behalf of the Department for Transport. This seminar is based on principles of </span><a href="http://rdrf.org.uk/"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Road Danger Reduction</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which aim to promote benign active travel and reduce t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he source of road danger. We are submitting a number of case studies which give an overview of work in this area, especially around training drivers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Training people who ride bicycles</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Why train cyclists? Surely anyone can ride a bike? Ideally the spaces w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here people live, work and shop should be accessible on foot and on bike without any special training, and this is largely the case. The majority of people who cycle manage perfectly well with little guidance and statistically, riding a bike is a low risk </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">activity per mile travelled. There are, however, many people who perceive cycling as more risky than it is, people who would cycle if they had help with gaining the skills and confidence to do so. Training  these people helps them make the transition from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">someone who is reluctant to ride due to perceived risk to some who can ride anywhere with confidence in a short time. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(One argument for separating people on bikes from people in cars is that many more people would take to cycling on road after a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">few mont</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">hs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of experience riding in a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">segregated environment. People who undergo cycle training can make this transition in 2-4 hours!)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Even confident people who already cycle can benefit from training. As with any activity input from an expert can increase effici</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ency thereby improving the enjoyment of cycling, perhaps increase peoples speed (by encouraging them to ride as part of the traffic flow) and definitely ensuring that what is a relatively low risk activity becomes even less risky.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">People who cycle are mor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e likely to ride their bikes more often, make longer trips and cycle in all seasons as evidenced in </span><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000166.pdf"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> research</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> commissioned by Transport for London in 2003.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000121.pdf"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000121.pdf"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Training people who drive to be aware of cyclists</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some Bikeability schemes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in London were delivering cyclists/driver awareness sessions  since 2007. These sessions were largely theoretical, classroom-based sessions. They were delivered to all people who drove for some London councils on council business. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Following the success </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of this scheme, Bikeability schemes were commissioned to develop a programme whereby lorry drivers, contracted by the councils, received on bike training in addition to a theory session. (This anecdotally fostered much empathy between some council’s driver</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s and local cyclists). This programme was replicated with bus companies (Abellio, Stagecoach and Go Ahead) who also agreed to go one step further and training bus driver trainers as cycling instructors in order to deliver this more sustainably in-house.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Encouraged by the success of the driver training TFL, in partnership with Bikeability schemes, developed an on-bike driver/cyclist awareness course that met HGV/PCV </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/driver-certificate-of-professional-competence-cpc/overview"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">CPC</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> outcomes. These courses were submitted to JAUPT, the CPC accrediting body by  Transport for London. Out of this came the Safe Urban Driving course (SUD) which is being promoted to many professional drivers who use London’s roads through the Freight </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Operators Recognition Scheme (FORS).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The one day training SUD course comprises of a practical and a theory module and contributes 7 hours towards the legal CPC requirement of 35 hours of professional training for drivers. The aims of this course are:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure passenger comfort and safety</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To know the social environment of road transport</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To make drivers aware of the risks of the road</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to adopt behaviour to help enhance the image of the company</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An outcome of the development of this training has been interes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t from professional drivers who are not required to undergo CPC training in particular the private can hire company Addison Lee who piloted this training for 20 drivers then trained their own trainers to deliver this on bike driver/cyclists awareness train</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing in-house.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Making cycle training a prerequisite of driver training may lead to better and more responsible drivers as well as drivers who can cycle and may feel happy about making some trips by bike rather than in a car. We are looking forward to input</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ting to the proposed Green Paper on young driver training </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Driver training case studies</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000207.pdf"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Volker Highways CPC</span></a><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000132.pdf"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">b.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000269.pdf"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Go Ahead cyclist awareness classroom sessions</span></a><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000269.pdf"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000270.pdf"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Addison Lee</span></a><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000270.pdf"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000270.pdf"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a href="http://www.cycletraining.co.uk/library/website/resources/lib0000000270.pdf"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Active promotion of cycling:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> While we are sure many submis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sions to the select committee will highlight the need to redesign the road environment helping to reduce the risk and the perception of risk, we believe cheaper immediate wins could be achieved by positive marketing of cycling as desirable low risk benign </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">activity that anyone can do.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Create a road sharing environment:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Bikeability and National Standard cycle training gives people on bikes the skills to share the road with people in motor vehicles by communicating to them through looking and road positioning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Ensuring that the speed differential between modes is low would encourage riders to move within the flow of traffic and discourage drivers from ‘punishing’ people on bikes using aggressive behaviour when the driver perceives the cyclists as ‘in their way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’. 20mph (or lower) speed limits in all urban areas, enforced through design and policing would help people share the road space</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Funding and promotion of adult cycle training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: rebranding it to remove the child-centred stigma attached (Urban riding skills </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">training perhaps?) would help adults make the transition from off road leisure riders to everyday cyclists in a short time. T</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Continued funding and promotion of Bikeability for young people:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through the Bikeability schemes and Youth Sports Trusts. Such fu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nding should be guaranteed across terms of government. Up-skilling people of all ages through training as well as messages about how to road share will minimise risk on the roads</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Funding and promotion of on-bike driver training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: While this has been happen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing for too short a time to accrue more than anecdotal evidence of the value of getting drivers on bikes there is definitely a case from the small amount of feedback received from participants (TfL have this data) to recommend that this scheme be scaled up</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> nationally and that anyone who drives a lorry or a bus on roads where people ride bikes should get such training. The training should also be rolled-out to all professional drivers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cycle training for anyone who a gets a driving licence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: If, as a society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we seriously wish to normalise cycling and minimise road risk, demonstrating the ability to ride on road and understand the basics of the highway code should be demonstrated on a bicycle before people are allowed a provisional driving licence.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TABS welco</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Transport Committee inquiry on cycling safety </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and looks forward to the renewed focus on cycling both in parliament and the media. We would be happy to contribute further by submitting additional evidence as required.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>